{{italic title}} The '''''Microsymphony''''' is a single-movement composition for [[orchestra]] by the American composer [[Charles Wuorinen]]. The work was commissioned by the [[Philadelphia Orchestra]] and was completed in 1992.<ref name="Score">[[Charles Wuorinen|Wuorinen, Charles]] (1992). [http://www.charleswuorinen.com/compositions/microsymphony/ Microsymphony]. Retrieved March 14, 2016.</ref> The piece was a finalist for the 1994 [[Pulitzer Prize for Music]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Others Recommended for Pulitzers |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=April 13, 1994 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-04-13/news/mn-45543_1_los-angeles-times |accessdate=March 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Suzuki |first=Dean |title=View from the West: New Hope for the Pulitzer |work=[[NewMusicBox]] |date=August 1, 2003 |url=http://www.newmusicbox.org/articles/view-from-the-west-new-hope-for-the-pulitzer/ |accessdate=March 14, 2016}}</ref>
==Composition== The ''Microsymphony'' has a duration of roughly 11 minutes and is composed in one continuous [[Movement (music)|movement]]. The seemingly contradictory title refers to the composition's relatively brief length, which is uncommon for a traditional [[symphony]].
===Instrumentation=== The work is scored for a large orchestra comprising four [[Western concert flute|flutes]] (4th doubling [[piccolo]]), three [[oboe]]s, three [[clarinet]]s (3rd doubling [[bass clarinet]]), two [[bassoon]]s, [[contrabassoon]], four [[French horn|horns]], three [[trumpet]]s in C, two [[trombone]]s, [[bass trombone]], [[tuba]], [[timpani]], three percussionists, [[Pedal harp|harp]], [[piano]], and [[String section|strings]].<ref name="Score" />
